    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Abinger Hall | Wotton, Surrey</placeName>
                    <date>June 25<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am staying at a friends’ house for rest, as I have lately been very unwell, &amp; am sorry to say that I stay till after the 6<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of July, so that I cannot see you at Down.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Shortly before leaving home, three weeks ago, I wrote to you at St. Louis thanking you for the last Report, which I have not yet had time to read, but which I am sure will interest me much, as have all the previous Reports.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I hope that you may have a pleasant tour &amp; remain, My dear Sir, Yours very sincerely, Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 Surrey] <hi rend="italic">before del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">2.1 , three weeks ago,] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10002F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to C. V. Riley, 30 May 1875</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Abinger Hall was the home of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1599.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Henry Farrer</ref>; CD stayed there from 3 June to 6 July 1875 (see CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)). Riley had travelled from America with <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1230.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Leonard Darwin</ref>, who was returning from the transit of Venus expedition, and apparently met with CD at Abinger (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6654.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Riley 1882</ref>, pp. 77, 80).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10002F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to C. V. Riley, 30 May 1875</ref> and nn. 2 and 3. Riley had sent CD the seventh annual report on noxious insects of Missouri (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6652.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Riley 1869–77</ref>, seventh report (1875)); Riley was state entomologist of Missouri. CD’s annotated copy of the report, and the previous ones sent by Riley, are in the Darwin Library–CUL.</note>
        </div>        
            
